Thirdly, methanogenesis was enhanced by the CQDs and PC (Fig. 8
                        ). The different substrates in the AD process led to multiple methanogenic pathways of simple organics [59]): acetate (Acetotrophic methanogen: CH3COO–+H+→CH4 + CO2,methanol, methylated amines, and methylated sulfides (Methylotrophic methanogen: Methyl-→CH4 + CO2); H2, CO2 (Hydrogenotrophic methanogen: 4H2 + CO2 → CH4 + 2H2O). However, the electron transfer processes of these three pathways render them inefficient for methanogenesis. Hydrotropic methanogenesis occurs at a low hydrogen partial pressure [22]. Various studies [23] have shown that carbon materials can establish DIET between fermentation bacteria and methanogen to directly convert CO2 to CH4 (8H++8e-+CO2 → CH4 + 2H2O). This results in a more efficient methanogenesis, with increased efficiency associated with DIET having a faster rate of electron transfer than hydrotropic and methylotrophic methanogenesis. In this work, the host–guest assembly carbon accelerant was introduced into AcoDMF. The host materials (CQDs) possessed excellent electron exchange capacity and improved the electrochemical properties of AcoD system [19], thereby enhancing the electron transfer between acetogen and methanogens; CQDs enriched methanogenic microorganisms (Methanosarcina and Methanobacterium) involved in the DIET process, which indicated that CODs could promote the methanogensis via DIET (Fig. 8). In addition, the PC and CQDs entered several other paths for electron transport. PC could allow anaerobic microorganisms and substrates to adhere to its surface and facilitated improved electron conduction, while CQDs with superior EEC simultaneously further enhanced the electron transfer of PC, resulting in an overall improvement of electron transfer efficiency, as indicated by CV and LSV (Fig. 7
                        a-b). Notably, when compared with the control group of a previous study (Table 5
                        ), the MF coupled with accelerant (CQDs and PC) promoted the breakdown of organic matter in AcoD [18].
